Web 3.0 Applications

Web 3.0 refers to the decentralized internet powered by blockchain, smart contracts, AI, and cryptography, 
where users own their data and digital assets.

Major Web 3.0 Applications
Application Area                              Description                          Examples
Decentralized Finance (DeFi)        Financial services without banks        Uniswap, Aave, Compound
Cryptocurrencies                    Peer-to-peer digital money              Bitcoin, Ethereum
NFTs                                Digital ownership of assets             OpenSea, Rarible
Decentralized Apps (dApps)          Apps running on blockchain              MetaMask, Brave
Smart Contracts                     Self-executing digital agreements       Ethereum Smart Contracts
DAOs                                Community-governed organizations        MakerDAO
Decentralized Storage               Secure data storage                     IPFS, Filecoin
Metaverse                           Virtual digital worlds                  Decentraland, The Sandbox
Digital Identity                    User-controlled identity                ENS, Civic
Supply Chain Tracking               Transparent logistics                   IBM Food Trust

 
Key Features of Web 3.0 Applications
  Decentralization
  Trustless transactions
  User data ownership
  High transparency
  Token-based economy

One-Line Summary
Web 3.0 applications enable decentralized, trustless, and user-owned digital ecosystems using blockchain technology.
 

